{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_romeo_ver02/data/sn84026749/100492696/1907112401/0703.xml":{"full_text":"mtrendance at the exposition was in\n\u2018conseguence reduced to the minimum,\n@ition of affairs resulted from wide and\nsevere criticism of the press following\n\u2018the opening event. Stories were sent\n\u2018throughout the country, telling of the\n~amcompleted condition of the exposition,\n\u2018the extortionate hotel and boarding\n\u201chouse rates, and of the miserable fail\n8 of the exposition management to\ng receive and entertain Its hon\n\u2018wored guests.\n80 broad and severe was the criticism\n\u2018that the exposition never recovered {rom\nfits effects. It ran along for several\n\u201cmonths with an average of from 3,00\n\u201cto 5,000 daily attendance. These figures\n\u201cinclude passes of all kinds.\n2\nRm\nand cause con\nare\nproperiy\n\nDebt Increased.\nWith such low gate receipts, the ex\nposition company gradually sank farther\nin debt. It had on its hands an expo\n\u2018sition, with numerous bhulldings, some\nuncompleted, and others without ex\n\u2018hibits, and mud holes for streets and\nsldewalks. During this period it seri\n\u201cously suffered from a long spell of rainy\nweather, which not only materially in\n\u201cterfered with the construction work, but\nwith the gate receipts.\n\n\n\n\n\nBy July 1 the cards seemed as (hough\n_they had been stacked against the expo\nsition. Without a dollar in the treasury,\n~@a salary list pilling up at the rate of\n\u201cabout $5,000 per day, and money needed\n\u201cto complete the show, drastic action\n\u201cmwas found imperative for relief. An\n.additional loan of $400,000 was sought.\n\u201cBeing already heavily involved in the\nexposition\u2019s finances, the banks and\ntrust companies of Norfolk and Ports\nmouth found themselves only able to\nraise about $65,000. The railroads with\n\u2018terminals at Norfolk and steamboat\n\u2018lines were then urged to pool interests,\n\u2018and they raised a sum estimated at be\nfween $200,000 and $300,000.\n\nExposition bonds were to be taken for\nthe money, and a condition that James\nDM. Barr, president of the Seaboard Air\nLine, become director general, super\n\u2018vise the expenditure, and have absolute\nxontrol of the exposition management.\nBarr Put in Charge.\nThe exposition stockholders and di\nFectors enacted the necessary amend\nMments to the by-laws of the corporation\nMn agreement with the demands of the\ngransportation lines, and Mr. Barr was\nlected and took charge, with the un\nderstanding that he receive no pay for\nservices. i\nImmediately upon the inceming of\nirector parr coniidence of the couatry\nas restored in the exposition and the\nattendance gradually increased. Mr.\nWBarr displayed excellent busines. abil\nHy, and soon had the exposition not\nonly completed, but on a paying basis.\n{The numerous concessionaires on the\ngWar Path ard in exhibit buildings, who\n4d suffered greatly financially, gave to\nr. Barr their unqualified support in\n\u2018one effort to make the big show a suc\nLess. Friction was not long in coming,\n\u00abchiefly over social affairs, and Mr. Barr\ntwice resigned, saying that he <ould not\nremain \u201cunder existing conditions,\u201d\n\u2018which was an allegation that the expo\nsition was not living up to its cuniract\nswith him. The railroads took the same\nwiew.\n80 did Secretary Cortelyou, who, in\nthe capacity of Government agent for\nthe collection of the $1,000,000 loan made\nthe exposition by the Government, and\na small fraction of which has been\nPaid. A minority of the directors then\n\u2018got together, accepted Barr's resigna\ntion, and elected Alva H. Martin di\nrector general. The railroads had pul\nwp their money as agreed, but with the\nexception of the payment of ons line,\nthe Chesapeake and Ohio, it had not\nyet been turned over to the exposition.\nThe money was withdrawn. This was\nthe most serious blow to the exposition\nand its creditors. 'The railroads claimed\nthat the exposition had broken its con\ntract with them.\n\nClash With Tucker.\nOne of the reasons which led to the\nresignation of Mr. Barr was the Barr\nTucker controyersy. This incident was\nenacted during the visit of Prince Wil\nhelm, son of the King of Sweden. It\nwas a question of social authority be\ntween these officials. Mr. Barr con.\ntended that his power of authority was\nbeing grossly ignored and requested the\nboard of directors to sustain the posi\ntion he took in the matter. This they\nrefused to do, and Mr. Barr immedi\nately handed in his resignation. At\nJeast two weeks elapsed before official\naction was taken by the board. During\n\u2018the interim not only the exhibitors, con\njeessionaires, and the State Commission\ners\u2019 Association at the exposition passed\nresolutions urging Mr. Barr to recon\nsider, but the business men of Norfolk\nmand Tidewater Virginia insisted that\n1\n\n\ne board of directors refuse to accept\n\u2018the resignation. Even more powerful\nMnfluences were brought to bear on the\n\n\nard of directors to carry out this de\nire,\nUrged bv Government.\n\nPES eR ey Ere TT ree are ee ve\nThe Government not only sent Assist\nt Secretary Edwards, of the Treasury\npartment, to see the exposition direc\nors, but Secretary Cortelyou wrote an\nmrgent letter to them in which he in\nsisted that the services of Mr. Barr to\nretained. He asked that they refuse\no accept his resignation, that they co\nperate with Barr and make the remain\nder of the exposition\u2019s life a success.\nTo these pleadings the board turned a\ndeat ear, accepted Mr. Barr's resigna\ntion and elected Alva M. Martin, a Nor\nolk banker, director general.\nIn face of all the trouble encountered,\ntne management of the exposition com\nipeny has voted to reopen the fair for\nia of four months next year. It\n\n\n\n\nLY\n5\nAgli Italiani.\nChristian Xander\n909 7\u2122 Strada N. W. Washington, D. C.\ncasa fondata nel 1865\nnegoziante importatore df vint e liguori d'Ttalia, Prancia, Germania\necc. e di California, e produttore di vini rossi di Virginia. Fornitore es\nclusivo per le famiglie.\nI Depositi riuniti in \u00a2ue edifizi formans il piu grandioso stabilimento\ndel paese. L/assortimento e da molii anni rinomato per la intelligen\ntissima selezione delle qualita.\ndelle 307 distinte bevande, che contiene\nFra queste si trovano per occasioni di feste i vini rossi e bianchi piu\nsquisiti del diversi paesi, insleme con eccellenti vinl della California e\ndella Virginia per I'uso quetidiane da tavola, Della Virginia vi sono due\nvini rossi al prezzi, di 0.7% e $2.25 la dozzina Inoltre vi sono le migliori\nqualitd di vermouth Italia, vim Ji Capri e l.acrima Christi, rosst e\nbianchi, e Chianti stravecchic rosso.\nLa, \u2018scelta delic bevande desiderate facile all\u2019esaminare le differenti\nqualita nello stabilimen\u2018o 99 Tma st. colla guida dci catalogo, ii quale,\nrichlesio 0 per posta o per teiefonc Main 274, immediatemente spedito.\n\u20148i parla italiano. {Attenzi-ne al numero 209.)\nis estimated by the Government authori\nties that an appropriation of between\n$45,000 and $0,000 will be required to\nmaintain the Federal exhibits for such\na period. Whether it will be the pur\npose of the exposition to ask Congress\nfor a further appropriation for other\npurposes has not been learned.\n\n\ni\n\nThe reopening plan is not meeting\nwith much encouragement. The State\nresident commissioners to the exposi\ntion, representing some thirty odd State\nbuildings, have gone on record as being\nunanimously opposed to the proposition.\nA meeting of the commercial exhibitors\nand the War Path concessionaires was\nalso held recently and there was about\nan equal division of sentiment in re\ngard to reopening among them.\n\n\n\n\nProposition to Government.\nThe air is full of rumors about the fu\nture of the exposition property. Per\nsistent has been the claim fcr months\nthat the fair projectors are looking\ntoward a sale 2f the property to the\nGovernment for use as a coalirg station,\nnaval training otation, and ordnance\ntesting ground. It is figured that with\nthe nunerous permanent buildings,\nmiles of concrete sidewalss and gravel\nstreets, two large piers besides the great\npliers owned by the Government, the\nGovernment would likely consider this\nan ideal plece of property to acquire.\nIt is understoosl that the exposition\ncompany expects to realize $5,000,000.\n\n\n\n\n\n1\n\n\nAnother scheme on foot is ic huild a\ncity on the exposition site\u2014either a\numiner r2sort or a manufactering cen\nter. For either purpose the location is\nconsidered ideal and profitable. From\nthe best of information it is the ulti\nmate intention of the exxposition com\npany, if the Government does not take\nover the property for its own use, to\nacquire, without cost, the magnificent\nGovernment piers, which will be used\nas a gateway to the new city, These\npiers were provided for in special fegis-.\nlation. The act provides that at the\nclose of the exposition the piers shall\nbe publicly sold by the Secretary of the\nTreasury to the highest bidder, the ex\n\n\n\n\n\n\nposition compary being designated as\na preferred bidder in case it should de\nsire the possession of the plers.\nGigantic Single Span.\nhis magalficent contribution of the\nvernment to the glory and beauty of\nthe ter-centennial celebration repre\nsents one of the most gigantic tasks\nof modern times. The grand piers, each\n2,500 feet long, 200 feet wide, are con\nnected at the extreme ends by the\nlongest single-span concrete bridge in\nAmerica. The piers form the great cen-|\nter piece oi tae exposition, inclosing\na water basin containing 1,280,000\nsquare feet of water surface and a\ndepth of about six or eight feet at\nhigh tide, just out into Hampton\nRoads from a central point on the ex\nposition grounds immediately -in front\nof the large auditorium building, Ra\nleigh square, and the grand plaza. At)\nthe outer corners of the basin stand\nhigh towers for the exhibits of the\nlighthouse service and the wireless\ntelegraph.\nBoth the exposition company and\nthe Government have come in for their\nshare of severe criticism on account\nof the lateness of completing these\npiers, which were formally dedicated\nSeptember 14. They were particularly\nadvertised as the principal attaction\nof the exposition to be ready for the\nopening day, or soon after. Blame for\ntheir completion at least two m uths\nearlier is charged against the dd la\ntory action of the exposition in ap\nproving the plans. On the other head,\nthe contractor, in beginning his work,\nhad three serious preblems to solve.\n\n\nQne was the labor conditions at _.he\nexposition grounds, which at that t me\nwere not altogether satisfactory, on ac\ncount of the thousands of men required\n\n\nMOFFATT\u2014Entered into life on Friday, No\nvember 22, 1907, at 3:30 a. m., at the resi\ndence of her daughter, Mrs. A. W. Tracy,\n1470 Newton street northwest, ELIZABETH\nADAMS MOFFATT, widow- of Charles A.\nMoffatt of Indianapolis, Ind., and mother\nof Mrs. C. F. Dickens Miss Adah T. Mof\nfatt, Mrs F. C. Getzen ianner and Mrs. 3.\nW. Tracy, all of Washington, D. C., and\nCharles Ansil Mcffatt and William J. Mof\nfatt. of Indianapolis\nJ. WILLIAM LEE,\nURDERTAXKER AND LIVERY.\n332 Pa. Ave. N. W., Washington, D. C.\nTelephone Main 1383.\nFUNERAL DESIGNS\nFUNERAL DESIGNS\nof every description\u2014moderately priced,\nLoans and Other Expenses\nOf Jamestown Exposition\nol\nhE\nGovernment Loan to Exposition........ be Bad LLG veeeees $1,000,000\nOther Government Loans and Ald ....coeovivvvenrneensens 2,000,000\nBailronds! LORR \u00abrv ortors sass or insnsat Ae sa Hess ve 200,000\nTotal Debt Remaining......... sere vr aveee ens sen y ceees 2,500,000\nNorfolk and Portsmouth Bankers\u2019 Loan........ TR IOPICUEREA 65,600\nCost of Government Piers... cscs creer csrncrsncnee aye 400,000\nAverage Daily Attendance........ccevvnvnnen meee FA 3,000\nDaily Salary Expense........... RAR Se CR I PIU BULLI 5,000\n\nEstimated Value of Property... ..coeevvcenincnnninnnnns eee. 5,000,000\n\nDied\nUNDERTAKERS\nTHE WASHINGTON TIMES, SUNDAY, NOVEMBER 24, 1907.\nEE\nfor other construction work; second, the\nuncertainty of the tido of action as in\nfluenced by almost the slightest wind;\nthird, the heavy wind storms to which\nthe waters off \u2018he exposition grounds\nere exposed. in winter and spring.\n\nThe question now arises is, \u00abwhut\nfuture use can be made of these picrs?\nThey rerresent a piece of concrete con\nstruction, wilch experts declare will\nstand for a century. The supersiruc\nture, which is for ornamental purposes\nonly, wiil probably crumble away in\ncourse of a y\u00e9ar or two, but the struc\nture, generally, will rernain intact for\nages. Why did the Government authori\nties plan and authorize such a tremen\ndous undertaking of permanent con\nstruction instead of a temporary pier?\nThat is the question asked by almost\nevery visitor to the exposition.\n\n\n\n\n\nChannel Necessary.\n\nIt is openly argued by naval experts\nthat, should the pliers be used for coal\ning purposes, it would be necessary to\ndredge a channel to the approach from\na point near Fort Wool, known ag the\n\u201cRipraps,\u201d a distance of two miles.\nThe channel would then, they declare,\nhave to be protected by the construc\ntion of a sea wall on either side for the\nentire distance. This improvement would\nentail an expenditure of millions of dol\nlars, As it is now, the water at high\ntide is only about six to eight feet deep\nat the extreme end of the Government\npliers This depth, with little variance,\nexter 8 to Fort Wool. Therefore, it is\npiain.; seen that only pleasure craft\nwith shallow draft Is enabled to ap\npreach and enter the basin of the piers.\n\n\n1\n\nThe Government has lent {its aid to\nthe Jamestown Exposition to the extent\nof nearly $3,000,000, This expenditure\nincludes the loan of $1,000,000; the con\nstruction of the Government piers at a\ncost of $400,000; the construction of five\nbuildings for Government exhibits; the\nconstruction and maintenance of an\narmy and navy club and a commission\ners\u2019 building to house Federal officials\nconnected with the exposition. What it\n\n\n\n\n\ncost the Government to mobilize some\nfifty odd battleships in Hampton Roads\nduring the period of the exposition has\nnot been estimated.\nFRANK P. SARGENT BETTER.\nFrank P. Sargent, Commissioner Gen\neral of Immigration and Naturalization,\nwho has been ili at his home, in this\ncity, some days, was greatly iniproved\nlast night. He was reported as resting\neasily and suffering but little. Mr. Sar\ngent has not been critically ill, as was\nrepoitad. In all probability he will be\nat his office some time this weelk.\n\n\nJOINS UNITED PRESS STAFF\nArwxine Perry Arnold, who has for\nnearly a year been ccuaected with the\nTennessean, of Nasbville, Teun. in an\neditorial capacity, has accepted a posi\ntion on the staff of the Washington\nbranch of the Unfitca Press Associa\ntions.\nARR fl a th a, is A AE a ein ry \u00aeT 59% 4322 9% 5 2 85 5S 8 0 FS 3\n$15 and $20 Imported\nFrench Batiste Waists\nTO CLOSE OUT\n1\nAll of our Imported French Batiste Waists,\nhand-made and hand-embroidered, trimmed with\nGerman and Val. laces, long or short sleeves. NO\nTWO ALIKE have been put in one lot.\nIncluded in this lot are some Imported French\nSilk Waists in pastel shades for evening wear.\nWe have been selling these waists at $15 and\n$20, but to close out quickly to make room for\nholiday stock we have marked them at\n$7.50\n9 WM EYE\nLoonie. BEE BEE. EL. BE. he. EE UR. EE ER ER Re a\nff SH\nto Te 12.50\nFeather\n\n$25\nDisplay of Xmas Novelties\nOur Holiday stock of Imported Novelties is now\ncomplete, and, should you wish, we will lay aside\nyour purchases until wanted, upon the payment\nof a deporit.\nLOUVRE GLOVE CO.\n031 F Street\nRaho eed 4 4 4&4 5 4 4a 444 4% vv \"BY SB Shhh SOY Bb AY\u201c BED DNYDY\n0\nBk fF EF RE FS F&O 0 OE ES 8 8 FF 8 8 FF 8 8 0 0 OO og oF 8 8 8 8 8 BS FF EE EE EB LE LO OFF E08\n\n\nfx Br TE ex oy. dr dr We fe Wr Sr Wr Wf\nPRESIDENT AND BRYAN\nAGREE ABOUT CURRENCY\nREFORMS FOR NATION\n(Continued from First Page.)\nprompt ard permanent restoration\nconfidence in banks and the !mmediate\nFrom the tax un these issues there\nwould be derived a revenue to the Gov\nernment, which, it is understoed, would\nbe, under this plan, set aside, at least\nso far as needed, for a guarantee fund\nto assure against losses on the circula\ntion of failed banks. The Government\nwould be toe general guarantor, inter\nposing its own unimpeachable credit for\nthe purpose of absolutely establishing\nconfidence, but taxing the issuing banks\nenough to assure that It should not lose\nby the guarantee.\n\n\nDetails of the plan, of course, remain\nto be worked out by Congr:2ss, and as to\nthese there is no intention on the part\nof the Administration to Jdiciate.\nBb\nMr. Bryan talked to the President\nabout the financial plan which the Ne\nbraskan had presented in his statement\nissued on Thursday evening. This is\nsimple and to the point. Mr. Bryan pro\nroses an act of Congress to jjuarant:e\nall deposits in national banks, with the\nidea of taxing the banks enough to as\nsure the Government against loss. He\nurges that this would instantly relieve\nthe money situation, because it would\nrestore complete confidence in the\nbanks, would draw forth money whieh\nhas gone intc hiding, and would make\neverybody willing to trust the Institu\ntiong with their deposits.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nBryan's Plan Pleases President.\nEven on this proposal Mr. Eryan did\nnot find the President unwilling to give\nserious consideration. Rather, it de\nvelcped, the President had been inter\nested in the idea, and inclined to the\nopirion that it was practicable and use\nful. He is understood to prefer the idea\nof a Government guarantee to the plan\nof raising a guarantee fund, feeling that\na guarantee would be just as efrective,\nwould not withdraw money from gen\neral eclrculation, and would not involve\nthe Governinent in any loss because the\nbanks guaranteed cqQuld be assessed to\nmeet losses sustained in case of failures.\nIt 1s not inferred that this plan of\nguaranteeing deposits is Included in the\nplan which the President will lay be\nfore Congress, but there is strong rea\nson for the belief that the President be\nlives there is merit In (he plan, and\nwould raise no objection to it.\nt\n\n\n\n\u00a7f\n\n\u2018\u201cTher\u00e9 has Leen objection to this\npian,\u201d said Mr. Bryan, \u2018on the ground\nthat it would work serious injury io\nStute banks. These would of cHurse\nnot have the benefit of the absolute\nguarantee of their deposits, and State\nbankers fear that they would see their\ncustomers taking money away in order\nto deposit it ir national banss, where\nit would be absolutely secure,\nStates Also Guarantors,\n\u201cMy answer to this is that the States\nshould follow the lead of the Federal\nGovernment by passing laws guarantec\ning, In lik: fashion, the deposits in their\nState and savings institutions. It Jocs\nnot seem to me to be different in prin\ncipie from the national guarantee of\nnational bank deposits, and would have\nthe same effect. Then we should see a\nLEH\nrestoration of normal business condi\ntions.\u201d\nThe President, Mr. Bryan, and Mr.\nMorgan ali agreed, it is said, in taking\nan optimistic view of the pfesent finan\ncial and business outlook. Th~ Presi\ndent's visitors were confident that the\nworst of the financial scare is past, that\nnormal conditions are fast returning,\nand that the public mind is becoming\nsettled in the conviction that there will\nbe no ioug-continued depression,\nJ. Pilerpont Morgan and George FP.\nBaker returned to New York at 3 o'clock\nyesterday afternoon.\n\u2014\u2014S\u2014\u2014\u2014 E\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014. \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014L W\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014 A \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014_\u2014 re\nstore Closes 12 o\u2019Clock Thanks- TICKE\u00aeS GIVEN WITH 1 SHOES\ngiving day Phone Main 7129\nrr\nThis Week\nHow about your Thanksgiving Footwear? Have you visited\nour place of business since we annexed the adjoining building?\nIf so, you will say that we have not only two of the hand\nsomest and best equipped stores in Washington, but the most reliable and best selected stocks of Men's,\nLadies\u2019, Boys\u2019, Misses\u2019, and Children\u2019s Footwear, including every up-to-date and attractive style, made to\nour special order by only the most reliable factories, with Thanksgiving prices that will surpass anythin\nJ L\never offered in high-class footwear.\nLadies\u2019 $2.50 Boots in Blucher and Ladies\u201d $2.00 Boots, in viet and Men's $6.00 Shoes, in patent colt\nlace styles. Close edges and ex- box calf; pointed and round toes; 1 kid, viel. and gun metal\ntension soles) vic, patent colt, and Blucher and lace. Dur- stralzht \u2018and swinz. lasts: Hi ham\nduil calf; high and low able and good looking 1 0 straight and swing lasts: Blucher,\nheels. The best mak- Spe MR Co button, and lace. No detail omitted,\ners\u2019 best efforts. Special Ladies\u2019 $4.00 Boots in all the most nothing slighted. We\nfashionable leathers, Cuban, Mili- fit the feet perfectly.\nies\u2019 on 2 Yeoh tary, and French Beels, also the Bpetial...co.iinensnssnences bd\nLadies 5 od Boots, in choice nor college hoots; firm, well\nected eathers; patent coit, vwvici, Ra 3 et ig\n3 SA L xs AR made and stylish; me\nand dull calf; narrow, wide, and dium. or narrow toes. Men's $5.00 Shoes in Bh cher and\nmedium toes; Cuban and Military Suecial  vutto in all the most fashionable\nSwaaga x\" BPOCIRL, Lc vsnstrrrnsrricanne yu n, tn\nheels You will take Ladies\